1
00:00:13,933 --> 00:00:16,390
- What are you doing?
- My book report.

2
00:00:16,558 --> 00:00:18,851
Didn't you just start this book
a half an hour ago?

3
00:00:19,324 --> 00:00:22,258
Yeah, I read the flap
and then the first chapter,

4
00:00:22,383 --> 00:00:24,732
then I totally figured out the ending,
so it's cool.

5
00:00:24,901 --> 00:00:28,693
- How do you know that you're right?
- You taught me how to draw conclusions.

6
00:00:29,232 --> 00:00:31,113
You know what you're doing,
don't you?

7
00:00:31,577 --> 00:00:33,658
Banking a whole afternoon
of video game time.

8
00:00:35,233 --> 00:00:37,385
You're operating
on incomplete information. It's sloppy,

9
00:00:37,510 --> 00:00:39,330
you're gonna find yourself
embarrassed by it.

10
00:00:39,669 --> 00:00:42,735
Dad, please, it's pretty obvious
to figure out what's gonna happen.

11
00:00:42,860 --> 00:00:44,527
Wilbur's gonna win the pig ribbon,

12
00:00:44,795 --> 00:00:47,360
and he and Charlotte
are gonna live happily ever after.

13
00:00:49,735 --> 00:00:50,735
All right,

14
00:00:51,594 --> 00:00:52,860
I'll tell you what.

15
00:00:52,985 --> 00:00:55,023
If you get an "A" on that report,

16
00:00:55,564 --> 00:00:57,973
- I'm gonna take you to Disneyland.
- Sweet!

17
00:01:00,849 --> 00:01:02,006
Good luck, kiddo.

18
00:01:10,010 --> 00:01:12,926
You were doing exactly
what I'm doing now

19
00:01:13,439 --> 00:01:14,939
when you poisoned...

20
00:01:15,429 --> 00:01:17,434
Mr. Camfini's pizza.

21
00:01:18,516 --> 00:01:20,204
Think about what you want
on this pizza.

22
00:01:20,556 --> 00:01:23,790
It's the last one you'll eat
before you go to prison... for murder.

23
00:01:27,931 --> 00:01:30,548
I could also do a calzone.
It's the same basic principle, right?

24
00:01:31,243 --> 00:01:33,676
Where's the pineapple?
You guys don't have any pineapple?

25
00:01:34,243 --> 00:01:35,243
Dad?

26
00:01:35,872 --> 00:01:38,139
- You gotta stop.
- I've made a pizza before.

27
00:01:38,308 --> 00:01:39,747
You've got the wrong guy.

28
00:01:39,934 --> 00:01:42,183
He's the only one
who couldn't possibly have done this.

29
00:01:42,308 --> 00:01:44,685
- Didn't you ever read the case file?
- Yeah, I read th...

30
00:01:44,810 --> 00:01:48,718
Went over the summary and part of...
I don't have time to read case files.

31
00:01:48,843 --> 00:01:50,109
Medical alert bracelet.

32
00:01:50,278 --> 00:01:52,250
- The guy can't handle nuts.
- What?

33
00:01:52,375 --> 00:01:54,935
Shawn, the poison
was dissolved in peanut oil.

34
00:01:55,060 --> 00:01:58,075
His hands would look like baseball mitts
if he even got near that poison.

35
00:01:59,703 --> 00:02:00,889
What'd I tell you?

36
00:02:11,381 --> 00:02:15,381
First of all, let me apologize
for this interruption of process.

37
00:02:16,599 --> 00:02:18,888
I borrowed $5
from my father last week,

38
00:02:19,056 --> 00:02:22,229
and he's decided that now
would be an appropriate time to collect.

39
00:02:22,354 --> 00:02:23,559
Here you go, pop.

40
00:02:23,728 --> 00:02:25,561
Here's your five clams.
Take it.

41
00:02:25,730 --> 00:02:27,104
Buy your lotto tickets.

42
00:02:27,272 --> 00:02:30,065
Waste it on false hopes,
easy dreams.

43
00:02:30,759 --> 00:02:32,610
Meanwhile,
I will go back to doing what I do,

44
00:02:32,807 --> 00:02:34,661
which is working for a living.

45
00:02:34,786 --> 00:02:37,664
Speaking of working for a living,
how can you, sir,

46
00:02:38,450 --> 00:02:40,117
stand there with a clean conscience,

47
00:02:40,285 --> 00:02:42,724
while I accuse
an innocent young man of murder,

48
00:02:42,849 --> 00:02:44,955
when it was in fact you...

49
00:02:46,015 --> 00:02:47,816
who poisoned Mr. Camfini's pizza?

50
00:02:47,941 --> 00:02:48,876
You did this?

51
00:02:53,475 --> 00:02:54,298
Yes, I did.

52
00:02:55,138 --> 00:02:57,092
I've had this place for 25 years.

53
00:02:57,260 --> 00:02:59,761
I wasn't gonna let anyone sell off
my place to some chain.

54
00:03:01,098 --> 00:03:03,015
- This is a family business.
- I know.

55
00:03:03,184 --> 00:03:04,454
I'm your nephew.

56
00:03:04,579 --> 00:03:06,685
You were gonna let him take me?

57
00:03:08,146 --> 00:03:10,412
You know what? My work here is done.
Jules, cuff him.

58
00:03:10,537 --> 00:03:12,737
Lassie, finish topping that pizza.

59
00:03:17,768 --> 00:03:19,646
I got here as fast as I could.
What did I miss?

60
00:03:19,771 --> 00:03:21,060
Just me nailin' that guy.

61
00:03:21,185 --> 00:03:23,084
What are you talking about?
I nailed the guy.

62
00:03:23,209 --> 00:03:24,662
How can you rewrite history?

63
00:03:25,019 --> 00:03:27,331
He wrote a term paper
on president Mitchell.

64
00:03:27,522 --> 00:03:30,131
The fact is,
I saved your ass in there once again.

65
00:03:30,256 --> 00:03:32,503
- It's not the first time.
- Name another.

66
00:03:32,671 --> 00:03:35,840
Are you kidding? When don't you come
to me for last-minute guidance?

67
00:03:37,460 --> 00:03:39,363
I'm in a slump.
Gimme a break.

68
00:03:39,670 --> 00:03:41,736
I'll give you this one
on a technicality.

69
00:03:41,861 --> 00:03:44,640
But all the other stuff you do,
does that fall under fatherly duties?

70
00:03:47,213 --> 00:03:49,314
Did that not sound like a thank you?

71
00:03:49,439 --> 00:03:50,732
Hello. Walter Snowden.

72
00:03:50,857 --> 00:03:53,816
I'd like to introduce myself
and say very impressive work.

73
00:03:53,984 --> 00:03:55,609
Thanks, Walt.
I'm Shawn Spencer.

74
00:03:55,778 --> 00:03:57,965
- This is my partner...
- Burton Guster.

75
00:03:58,090 --> 00:04:00,155
Or should I say Ghee Buttersnaps

76
00:04:00,323 --> 00:04:03,909
or Lavender Gooms
or Clementine Wooliesocks, perhaps?

77
00:04:05,656 --> 00:04:07,905
- This guy really is a fan.
- A fan or a stalker.

78
00:04:08,030 --> 00:04:11,041
Ghee Buttersnaps was said on a secure
military base with no one else around.

79
00:04:11,209 --> 00:04:13,961
Let's just say I've been following
your work for quite a while now,

80
00:04:14,248 --> 00:04:16,693
and this last is very impressive.

81
00:04:16,969 --> 00:04:19,404
I thought you were going
to accuse that first gentleman.

82
00:04:19,801 --> 00:04:21,719
Would have been
completely ridiculous.

83
00:04:23,638 --> 00:04:27,641
I wouldn't say completely ridiculous.
He did have a douchey face.

84
00:04:27,976 --> 00:04:30,078
I saw what you were up to.
You turned it around.

85
00:04:30,203 --> 00:04:33,246
You created a false sense of security
for the real culprit,

86
00:04:33,371 --> 00:04:35,911
and then you coerced
a confession out of him.

87
00:04:36,036 --> 00:04:37,474
I mean, that was just...

88
00:04:39,279 --> 00:04:40,070
Brilliant.

89
00:04:40,238 --> 00:04:42,948
Let's just say that I am amazing
and leave it at that.

90
00:04:44,079 --> 00:04:45,491
I'd like to offer you a job.

91
00:04:46,662 --> 00:04:48,787
Thank you, but no, thank you.
He already has a job.

92
00:04:48,976 --> 00:04:50,929
Now, this is for the both of you,
actually.

93
00:04:51,458 --> 00:04:54,043
I run a fairly well-known
private security firm,

94
00:04:54,415 --> 00:04:57,880
and I'm working for a gentleman
who is quite... important.

95
00:04:58,669 --> 00:05:01,634
Walt, our jobs require that we go
shirtless at any given moment,

96
00:05:02,009 --> 00:05:04,548
and this, no offense,
sounds a little dry.

97
00:05:05,013 --> 00:05:08,328
It's a two-week operation.
I'll offer you $8,500 a day.

98
00:05:09,684 --> 00:05:11,477
- Do the math.
- Gus, do the math.

99
00:05:11,732 --> 00:05:13,081
That's a lot of money.

100
00:05:14,054 --> 00:05:15,798
What would we be doing exactly?

101
00:05:15,923 --> 00:05:18,358
You'd be part
of a prestigious think tank.

102
00:05:18,483 --> 00:05:21,278
- A think tank?
- A hand-picked assembly of experts,

103
00:05:21,446 --> 00:05:24,907
who would be working with my client,
Mr. Ashton Bonaventure.

104
00:05:25,548 --> 00:05:27,701
- The billionaire businessman?
- That's fantastic.

105
00:05:27,987 --> 00:05:30,187
I love that guy.
I love his mane.

106
00:05:30,312 --> 00:05:31,997
He's looking for new product ideas.

107
00:05:32,321 --> 00:05:33,582
No product ideas.

108
00:05:33,910 --> 00:05:36,543
He will be after I pitch him
the concept for the electric sponge.

109
00:05:36,711 --> 00:05:38,419
This has nothing to do
with businesses.

110
00:05:38,589 --> 00:05:40,454
So what will we be doing?

111
00:05:41,113 --> 00:05:42,925
Preventing his assassination.

112
00:06:02,237 --> 00:06:04,405
Psych 414
"Think Tank"

113
00:06:04,573 --> 00:06:07,293
Timing: Psych Team
www.sous-titres.eu

114
00:06:09,602 --> 00:06:12,172
The latest threat
on Mr. Bonaventure's life

115
00:06:12,297 --> 00:06:14,074
has been alarmingly precise.

116
00:06:14,199 --> 00:06:17,599
It states he will not survive
his speech in Santa Barbara.

117
00:06:20,964 --> 00:06:22,798
Any questions
before we get in the room?

118
00:06:24,740 --> 00:06:27,641
When will Gus and I be riding
in Mr. Bonaventure's hot air balloon?

119
00:06:27,766 --> 00:06:30,388
I don't even see
where that is a part of your duties.

120
00:06:30,513 --> 00:06:31,345
I see.

121
00:06:31,470 --> 00:06:34,439
Can I ride on the back of his jet ski
while he performs water doughnuts?

122
00:06:34,564 --> 00:06:37,033
I don't see
how that'll help protect him.

123
00:06:37,367 --> 00:06:40,136
Will he at least leave the outgoing
message on my answering machine?

124
00:06:40,261 --> 00:06:44,250
I believe in doing whatever it takes
to stimulate the creative process,

125
00:06:44,375 --> 00:06:47,145
within limits, and to that effect,

126
00:06:47,529 --> 00:06:51,662
I have addressed all of the items
on your contract rider.

127
00:06:51,787 --> 00:06:52,578
Rider?

128
00:06:52,850 --> 00:06:55,998
We have people looking
for your regulation-size trampoline,

129
00:06:56,296 --> 00:06:58,609
the packs of Big League Chew,

130
00:06:59,169 --> 00:07:02,796
and, of course, Mr. Guster's
official NBA "let's blast it" air horn.

131
00:07:02,975 --> 00:07:05,477
- I didn't want one of those.
- No, they'll find it.

132
00:07:06,176 --> 00:07:08,355
This is where your work begins.

133
00:07:08,480 --> 00:07:12,040
Now, the experts inside here
are the brightest minds in their fields.

134
00:07:12,165 --> 00:07:14,354
The ideas
will be flying around fast.

135
00:07:14,479 --> 00:07:17,895
Now we'll go over every attack
scenario imaginable.

136
00:07:18,104 --> 00:07:20,554
Mr. Bonaventure's life
depends upon it.

137
00:07:21,223 --> 00:07:22,611
Hope you're ready.

138
00:07:26,623 --> 00:07:27,673
Oh, my God.

139
00:07:28,283 --> 00:07:30,783
- Look at all the Skittles!
- You ordered them, Mr. Spencer.

140
00:07:31,482 --> 00:07:34,828
I'd like to introduce you
to your fellow think tank members.

141
00:07:35,235 --> 00:07:37,394
This is Fred Collins Boyd,

142
00:07:37,519 --> 00:07:40,000
who is a retired agent
for the secret service.

143
00:07:40,173 --> 00:07:42,123
He was hand-picked
by president Reagan.

144
00:07:42,422 --> 00:07:43,921
Reagan was the one after Mitchell?

145
00:07:44,236 --> 00:07:46,487
President Mitchell
was played by Kevin Kline in <i>Dave</i>.

146
00:07:46,612 --> 00:07:48,383
- He's a fictional character.
- No.

147
00:07:48,551 --> 00:07:51,645
Dave was a fictional character
who looked like president Mitchell.

148
00:07:52,360 --> 00:07:54,389
And Svetlana Progoyovic,

149
00:07:54,557 --> 00:07:57,817
formerly an independent contractor
working with government agencies,

150
00:07:57,942 --> 00:07:59,186
including the K.G.B.

151
00:07:59,363 --> 00:08:03,273
She's now working for the American
government in a preventative capacity.

152
00:08:03,442 --> 00:08:06,235
- Independent contractor. That mean...
- Hit woman? Yes.

153
00:08:06,403 --> 00:08:08,445
- I shouldn't try...
- Don't even think about it.

154
00:08:08,614 --> 00:08:12,407
And rounding out our team is Alan Zenuk,
who graduated from M.I.T.

155
00:08:12,575 --> 00:08:14,576
And is now
a leading crime statistician,

156
00:08:15,109 --> 00:08:16,829
dealing with odds and probabilities.

157
00:08:17,305 --> 00:08:19,998
I see. But didn't Winnie
from <i>The Wonder Years</i> also do that,

158
00:08:20,327 --> 00:08:23,418
and wouldn't it have been way cooler
to have her instead?

159
00:08:23,746 --> 00:08:26,296
And I'd like to introduce you
to Shawn Spencer

160
00:08:27,189 --> 00:08:30,342
and Burton Guster,
who started a psychic detective agency

161
00:08:30,510 --> 00:08:33,762
four years ago and have since solved
an impressive number of cases

162
00:08:33,930 --> 00:08:35,749
for the local police department.

163
00:08:35,874 --> 00:08:38,329
- Gentlemen, have a seat.
- All right.

164
00:08:39,328 --> 00:08:42,980
And, of course, you all know by now
this is our client,

165
00:08:43,300 --> 00:08:45,064
maverick billionaire,
Ashton Bonaventure.

166
00:08:46,234 --> 00:08:50,111
He is an innovator on the cutting edge
of the technological industry.

167
00:08:50,500 --> 00:08:53,574
That makes sense. I saw on Cribs that
he has a soda fountain in his bedroom.

168
00:08:54,532 --> 00:08:57,119
Yes, well, oddly enough,
that is correct as well.

169
00:08:57,287 --> 00:09:00,965
He also turned Wall Street upside down
when he bought out Tetron Tech in '98.

170
00:09:01,333 --> 00:09:04,626
- Thousands of people lost their jobs.
- Mr. Guster is on point, actually.

171
00:09:05,380 --> 00:09:07,356
You do not do as well as he has done

172
00:09:07,756 --> 00:09:10,678
without leaving a tidal wave of enemies
in your wake,

173
00:09:10,803 --> 00:09:13,926
and there have been three attempts
on his life in the last two years.

174
00:09:14,632 --> 00:09:17,931
It has become painfully apparent
that there are blind spots

175
00:09:18,099 --> 00:09:19,725
in his security detail,

176
00:09:19,893 --> 00:09:22,269
and it is your job
to tell us what they are.

177
00:09:22,445 --> 00:09:26,400
If a bad guy can do it, I want us
to have considered it beforehand.

178
00:09:26,734 --> 00:09:28,650
- Any questions?
- Yes, I have a question

179
00:09:28,775 --> 00:09:31,235
for the statistician formerly known
as Kenneth Branagh.

180
00:09:32,135 --> 00:09:34,906
Without looking, can you tell me exactly
how many Skittles are in this bowl?

181
00:09:35,425 --> 00:09:37,367
Sorry.
And what is the probability

182
00:09:37,655 --> 00:09:39,786
that Gus will choose a green one?

183
00:09:40,638 --> 00:09:43,451
Excuse me. What brings
Mr. Bonaventure to Santa Barbara?

184
00:09:43,576 --> 00:09:45,292
The purpose of the visit

185
00:09:45,460 --> 00:09:47,436
is the company's annual board
of directors address

186
00:09:47,561 --> 00:09:49,795
and to announce the rollout
of a major new product.

187
00:09:50,626 --> 00:09:54,134
Perhaps we should hear the rest
from Mr. Bonaventure himself.

188
00:09:55,428 --> 00:09:57,888
<i>Hello, team.
Thank you for participating.</i>

189
00:09:58,828 --> 00:10:01,031
<i>I can't imagine what it's like</i>

190
00:10:01,156 --> 00:10:03,769
<i>to be in your shoes right now,
having your responsibilities.</i>

191
00:10:04,144 --> 00:10:07,210
<i>Just know
that I will do whatever I can</i>

192
00:10:07,335 --> 00:10:10,018
<i>to help you keep me alive out there,
all right?</i>

193
00:10:10,443 --> 00:10:12,653
We're here to serve you, sir,
so relax.

194
00:10:12,822 --> 00:10:14,696
- We're on top of it.
- Mr. Bonaventure?

195
00:10:15,208 --> 00:10:16,844
Spencer... Shawn Spencer here.

196
00:10:17,492 --> 00:10:20,869
Do you think that there is a market
for a comb that works while you sleep?

197
00:10:23,415 --> 00:10:25,540
You have to push the button to talk.

198
00:10:27,254 --> 00:10:30,170
- Can you...
- No. I'm not gonna ask him again.

199
00:10:32,430 --> 00:10:34,299
He went scrooge on me.
Did you hear that?

200
00:10:35,844 --> 00:10:38,512
If there's nothing more,
let's get to work.

201
00:10:43,106 --> 00:10:46,103
This is a schematic of the building
where we think the attacker will strike.

202
00:10:47,144 --> 00:10:50,471
I'm lookin' at the service entrance
to the lower kitchen of the hotel here.

203
00:10:50,596 --> 00:10:51,699
It is off-limits.

204
00:10:51,824 --> 00:10:54,444
You cannot control a working environment
with that many moving pieces.

205
00:10:54,612 --> 00:10:57,030
I agree. Most breaches
would occur in that kitchen.

206
00:10:57,199 --> 00:11:00,575
The only tactic here is to make
the security team look the other way.

207
00:11:00,744 --> 00:11:02,202
Give me that map. I'll show you.

208
00:11:02,779 --> 00:11:04,079
We're not participating.

209
00:11:04,248 --> 00:11:06,221
They might
as well be speaking Australian.

210
00:11:06,346 --> 00:11:08,886
Now, look, it's like part giraffe,
part Loch Ness monster.

211
00:11:09,252 --> 00:11:10,308
Say something.

212
00:11:15,659 --> 00:11:17,125
I'm having a vision.

213
00:11:17,549 --> 00:11:18,635
Mr. Snowden.

214
00:11:19,679 --> 00:11:21,680
You still care for her very deeply,
don't you?

215
00:11:22,536 --> 00:11:23,557
That's correct.

216
00:11:27,738 --> 00:11:28,895
Svetlana?

217
00:11:29,475 --> 00:11:31,974
You recently moved
into a new residence, did you not?

218
00:11:32,099 --> 00:11:33,665
Congratulations.
Very sexy.

219
00:11:33,790 --> 00:11:35,368
Lava lamps, yes?

220
00:11:36,655 --> 00:11:39,484
- What does that have to do with that?
- I'm not sure yet, Boyd.

221
00:11:39,609 --> 00:11:40,866
That is how my gift works.

222
00:11:41,034 --> 00:11:43,618
It's like acid reflux,
but instead of acid,

223
00:11:43,884 --> 00:11:46,518
it's psychic-ness.
It's psychic-ness reflux.

224
00:11:46,956 --> 00:11:49,750
- I'll tell you when you're gonna die.
- Thanks for the parlor tricks, but no.

225
00:11:50,441 --> 00:11:54,087
If you don't mind, we're trying
to figure out what we're supposed to do

226
00:11:54,255 --> 00:11:57,247
if bullets fly in this tight kitchen
proximity here,

227
00:11:57,372 --> 00:11:59,216
so if you don't have
anything on topic.

228
00:11:59,341 --> 00:12:00,302
<i>Under Siege.</i>

229
00:12:00,470 --> 00:12:02,262
Seagal used a spatula
to deflect bullets.

230
00:12:02,430 --> 00:12:04,472
So you're saying
we arm our people with spatulas?

231
00:12:04,642 --> 00:12:07,767
No, I'm saying it was pretty cool,
and he's <i>Above the Law</i> again.

232
00:12:08,500 --> 00:12:11,480
I calculate the probability of that
occurring to be 0.0%.

233
00:12:14,266 --> 00:12:17,420
Let's switch to explosives
as a present threat.

234
00:12:17,737 --> 00:12:20,447
I've seen tiny plastique explosives
in cell phones.

235
00:12:21,018 --> 00:12:22,449
